    "\n",
    "The ranking was especially helpful. Putting the drinks on a clear healthiest-to-least-healthy scale, with scores and short explanations, made the trade-offs very easy to grasp. I didn‚Äôt have to decode vague health claims or marketing language; the logic behind each placement was spelled out plainly. I also appreciated that the tone was direct but not alarmist. Sugary sodas and energy drinks were criticized firmly, but in a way that felt grounded in evidence rather than moralizing.\n",
    "\n",
    "Another strength was balance. Water was correctly treated as the baseline, but the analysis didn‚Äôt stop there. Drinks like tea, milk, coconut water, and oral rehydration solutions were handled with nuance, acknowledging both benefits and limitations. That made the review feel realistic and usable in day-to-day life rather than idealized or dogmatic.\n",
    "\n",
    "What worked particularly well was how the advice translated into practical guidance. The takeaway that most people really only need water or sparkling water, and that electrolyte drinks are situational, helped cut through a lot of noise in the hydration and ‚Äúwellness‚Äù space. It reframed the question away from ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs the best product?‚Äù toward ‚Äúwhat problem am I actually solving?‚Äù\n",
